library(tidyverse) install.packages(assertr) library(assertr) library(skimr) library(ggforce)

set.seed(888) # To ensure consistent results from non-deterministic procedures rm(list=ls()) # Removes all variables

compas.df = read_csv(https://raw.githubusercontent.com/propublica/compas-analysis/master/compas-scores.csv)

skim(compas.df)

#There are a lot of missing values, including 742 missing from c_case_number, 749 from c_case_desc, and 8054 from r_case_number. Overall, 15 variables having missing values. There are 6 unique races in the dataset. There is string data which will likely be a bit more difficult to work with depending on what I want to do.

error.df = compas.df %>%
  chain_start %>%
  assert_rows(num_row_NAs, within_bounds(0, 1), everything()) %>%
  assert(within_bounds(0, Inf), priors_count) %>% # priors count is non negative
  verify(age>17 & age<90) %>% # making sure they are all adults
  insist_rows(maha_dist, within_n_mads(10), everything()) %>%
  chain_end(error_fun = error_df_return)

Error in svd(X) : infinite or missing values in 'x'

ggplot(compas.df, aes(priors_count)) +
  geom_histogram()
###strong skew to the right, majority of people do not have priors

ggplot(compas.df, aes(v_decile_score))+
  geom_histogram()

###minimum and most common v decile score is just under 1

ggplot(compas.df, aes(r_jail_in))+
  geom_histogram()

###seems to be a unimodal histogram indicating that most people were in jail between 2014-2015 however I would assume that such drastic change means they simply do not have as much information or there is missing information for years prior and after

ggplot(compas.df, aes(x = age, y = priors_count)) +
  geom_point()
###there does not seem to be a strong correlation with age and amount of priors

ggplot(compas.df, aes(x=age, y =v_decile_score))+
  geom_point()

###younger people are more likely to have a higher score

ggplot(compas.df, aes(x = race, y = priors_count))+
  geom_point()

###the majority of people with prior convictions are African American

ggplot(compas.df, aes(x = race, y = juv_fel_count))+
  geom_point()

###majority of people with a juvenile felony are African American with the exclusion of one

c_select = compas.df %>% select("age", "juv_fel_count", "priors_count", "v_decile_score", "days_b_screening_arrest")

long.compas.df = c_select %>% mutate(id = row_number()) %>% 
  pivot_longer(age:days_b_screening_arrest, names_to = "variables", values_to = "values")

scaled.long.compas.df = long.compas.df %>% group_by(variables) %>% mutate(s.values = scale(values))

ggplot(scaled.long.compas.df, aes(variables, s.values)) +
  geom_line(aes(group = id), linewidth = .1,size=1, alpha = .2) +
  coord_flip()
